</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div></div></div><h1 id='conforming-to'><a href='#conforming-to'>CONFORMING TO</a></h1><div data-for='conforming-to' data-hide><div class='section' data-for='conforming-to'><div data-more>
<p>These are BSD functions, present in glibc. They are not standardized in POSIX.</p>
</div></div></div><h1 id='notes'><a href='#notes'>NOTES</a></h1><div data-for='notes' data-hide><div class='section' data-for='notes'><div data-more>
<p>The <strong>const</strong> modifiers were added to the structure pointer arguments of <a href='openpty'>openpty</a>() and <a href='forkpty'>forkpty</a>() in glibc 2.8.</p>
<p>In versions of glibc before 2.0.92, <a href='openpty'>openpty</a>() returns file descriptors for a BSD pseudoterminal pair; since glibc 2.0.92, it first attempts to open a UNIX 98 pseudoterminal pair, and falls back to opening a BSD pseudoterminal pair if that fails.</p>
</div></div></div><h1 id='bugs'><a href='#bugs'>BUGS</a></h1><div data-for='bugs' data-hide><div class='section' data-for='bugs'><div data-more>
<p>Nobody knows how much space should be reserved for <code>name</code>. So, calling <a href='openpty'>openpty</a>() or <a href='forkpty'>forkpty</a>() with non-NULL <code>name</code> may not be secure.</p>
</div></div></div><h1 id='see-also'><a href='#see-also'>SEE ALSO</a></h1><div class='section' data-for='see-also'><div data-more>
